Â§ Computational SierpiÅ„ski Space and Algebras over the Sphere Spectrum

There is a deep analogy between partial computations and quantum transducers.
Working out this analogy in the framework of Homotopy Type Theory leads to an
interesting category of types known in literature as algebras over the Sphere
Spectrum.

Â§Â§ Preliminaries: Maybe-monad, the Boolean and Discretly-Pointed Types
By `ğ”¹[T]` (also known as `Maybe[T]` or `Optional[T]`) let's denote the type
  @Family ğ”¹[T]:
    Value(t : T)
    Nothing
The type `ğ”¹ := ğ”¹[Unit]` can be naturally identified with boolean type, maps
`T -> ğ”¹` classify decidable predicates on `T`.

The functor `ğ”¹[_]` is naturally forms a monad. Its Eilenberg-Moore category
is the category of pointed types with maps preserving the basepoint. This
category is a pointed (has zero object ğ”¹[Nothing] â‰… Unit) closed symmetric
monoidal category with smash product as tensor product and ğ”¹ as its unit.
The presence of the canonical basepoint-preserving map into ğ”¹ guarantees
that basepoint is discrete in each type (i.e. the property `p = basepoint`
is decidable for each object of the category). This category has all limits
and colimits of the ambient category, thus at least finitely complete and
cocomplete.

