The Kleisly category for `ğ”¹[_]` consists of types of the form `ğ”¹[T]` with maps
arising from maps `X -> ğ”¹[Y]`. It can be also viewed as a subcategory of the 
EM-category, consisting only of the types of the form `ğ”¹[T]` with `Nothing` as
basepoint. This category is still a pointed symmetric monoidal category with
zero object ğ”¹[Nothing] and âˆ§-unit object ğ”¹, it still has all colimits of the
ambient category, but it doesn't have any nontrivial limits and is not closed.
 
Â§Â§ Partial Computations
By `â„§[T]` let's denote the type of computations returning values of the type
`T` but possibly diverging at some inputs. Morally, elements of `â„§[T]` should
be given by functions
  compute(timeout : Nat) : ğ”¹[T]
returning either `Value(t)` if computation succeeds within `timeout` of steps
or `Nothing` otherwise with additional property that increasing timeout never
changes `Value(t)` to something else. Furthermore computations yielding same
results should be identified regardless of minimal timeout leading to result,
and it must be provable that `â„§[_]` is naturally a monad, which requires
definition to be a bit more involved.

Recently Altenkirch et al. [1] have proposed a particularily nice definition
of `â„§[T]`:
  @Family â„§[T]:
    â„§-extensionality(a b : â„§[T], a âŠ‘ b, b âŠ‘ a) : (a = b)
    Computation(c(timeout : Nat) : â„§[T], âˆ€(n : Nat), c(n) âŠ‘ c(n + 1))
    Value(t : T)
    âŠ¥
	
    @Family _âŠ‘_ : (a b : â„§[T]) -> Prop:
      refl(x : â„§[T]) : x âŠ‘ x
      bott(x : â„§[T]) : âŠ¥ âŠ‘ x 
      mono(:c, :p) : Computation(c, p) âŠ‘ d -> âˆ€(n : Nat), c(n) âŠ‘ d
      nomo(:c, :p) : âˆ€(n : Nat), c(n) âŠ‘ d -> Computation(c, p) âŠ‘ d

Note that computation `c` maps to `â„§[T]` instead of `ğ”¹[T]` used in the naÃ¯ve
formulation, and the definition of `â„§[T]` is mutually inductive with definition
of _âŠ‘_, thus â„§[T] is a Higher Inductive-Inductive Type. It can be shown that it
is set-truncated if `T` is, and naturally forms a monad, which gives a rise to
the Kleisly category of types `â„§[T]` and maps between them arising from maps of
the kind `X -> â„§[Y]`. It's a cocartesian category with zero object `â„§[Empty]`,
hence a pointed category. It is not closed and admits no direct products, but
can be equipped with a smash product `â„§[X] âˆ§ â„§[Y] -> â„§[X Ã— Y]` with neutral
element `â„§` := `â„§[Unit]` making it a symmetric monoidal category.

The type `â„§` is analogous to the boolean, maps `T -> â„§` classify semidecidable
properties on `T`, so we'll call it the SierpiÅ„ski Space.

This notion of partial computability enables definition of semi-deterministic
combinator `c +â‚eâ‚ g` that interleavingly computes `c` and `g` and returns the
value whichever returns first, given an evidence `e : c âˆ¥ g` that `c` and `g`
never terminate both, or agree on their results if they do. Composition of the
above mentioned Kleisli category distribute over `+`: `f(a + b) = f(a) + f(b)`
whenever either of sides defined. The operation `+` has neutral element âŠ¥ and
is symmetric (associative and commutative). Besides that, it is idempotent and
admits countable completion, i.e. semi-deterministic sums of countably infinite
lists of âˆ¥-compatible functions can be formed. This means in particular, that
â€“ the type of maps `T -> â„§` almost satisfies axioms of a topology:
  it contains constant maps `âŠ¥` and `Value(âˆ—)` corresponding to trivially true
  and trivially false predicates, is closed under âˆ§-products providing finite
  intersections of predicates and under +-sums providing utmost countably
  infinite unions (arbitrary unions would yield a genuine topology, countable
  unions suffice for completely separable spaces).
â€“ even when we're working in a model where all functions are continious, we can
  represent arbitrary measurable functions: by Lusin's theorem all measurable
  functions `X -> Y`, `X` being a completely separable space, can be obtained
  by combining a countable collection of âˆ¥-compatible continious partial maps
  `X -> â„§[Y]` that remain continious when restricted to the domain where they
  terminate.

By `X â¤ Y` let's denote the type `(f : X -> â„§[Y], Â¬{X | f(x) = âŠ¥})`, i.e. the
subtype of partial functions `X -> â„§[Y]` with negatively expressed (hence mere)
property that they always terminate. The type `X â¤ Y` contains all measurable
functions from `X` to `Y` in all models of HoTT where the Î -types contain all
continious functions from `X` to `Y`. Maps `_â¤_` clearly form a category, but
it remains to check whether this category is a closed symmetric monoidal one,
as in the classical case [2].

We'll refer to the type `T -> â„§` as "computational topology of T" (as already
mentioned, it almost satisfies the axioms of a topology, the difference being
irrelevant for most cases of interest).
The computational topology of the Cauchy Reals from the HoTT book contains all
rays of the form `{x : â„ | x < r}` and `{x : â„ | x > r}`, finite intersections
and utmost countable unions theirof, so it has provides at least as many open
and as many closed subsets as the standard topology on `â„`.
