It is quite easy to see that the computational topology of the types `â„§[T]`
themselves contains the constant maps `âŠ¥` and `Value(âˆ—)` and the map `id`,
providing closed subsets `â„§[T]`, `âŠ¥` and `{x : â„§ | x = âŠ¥}`. Existence of any
other closed subsets can be used to construct a "negation" map on `â„§ -> â„§`, 
hence implies LPO (ğ”¹ â‰… â„§) and makes all computational topologies discrete.
We can prohibit it by stating that `(â„§ = â„§)` is contractible, which is exactly
statement of having no proper clopen (decidable) subsets. This assumption also
prohibits all types `â„§[T]` any computationally closed sets besides `â„§[T]`, `âŠ¥`
and `{x : â„§ | x = âŠ¥}`.

The Eilenberg-Moore category â„§-Mod for the `â„§[_]`-monad is very similar to the
Eilenberg-Moore category for the `ğ”¹[_]`-monad: it consists of pointed types
and basepoint-preserving morphisms, is a pointed closed symmetric monoidal
category with zero object `â„§[Nothing]` and âˆ§-unit object â„§, has lots of (at
least all finite) limits and colimits. Due to the canonical map into the
âˆ§-unit â„§ type and canonical maps from the very same type into every object
T of this for every element of T, computational topology of the objects of
the EM-category is severely restricted: basepoint has to be closed subset
and no other point is allowed to be closed unless we are willing to accept
LPO (or if we insist on `(â„§ = â„§)` being contractible). At the same time
under assumption of a nonreusable â„§-oracle, computational topology of the
types `â„§[T]` gets equivalent to `ğ”¹[T]`, i.e. that of `T` with adjoined
discrete point.

Unfortunatelly, this category has no trace of semi-deterministic summation.
We would like to construct a similar category where types are naturally
equipped by such operation, so that it would naturally include the Kleisli
category for `â„§[_]` as a subcategory, and have all the nice properties of
the EM-category like having enough limits and and being (locally?) closed.

